snippet.textDisplay:
EP.9 failed to explain, at least to me, the method of how Palp's body was preserved and protected from fall, and how his body was spirited away before final detonation of DS2 above Forrest Moon. Not to mention how such a large section of DS2 was propelled to Endor's Water Moon, and not into Forrest Moon's gravity well. Or in 35 years, Palps did not attempt to recover Sith Wayfinder holocron. There was a mention of Palp's favorite SSD , Eclipse, disappearing and not being accounted for,.
In my view, the Rebellion from EP.4-6 failed in its objective. THey lost the Galactic Civil War up to then. The essence of what was Palpatine's Empire , survived and merely did a temporary retrograde. As a stay-behind, Palpatine activated Contingency plan, per canon, as shown in Battlefront II. Contingency was scuttled. So Final Order fleet's mission was to complete it. I suppose that would be how Palpatine would see revenge. But revenge is not a strategy, and it is not an objective. Completion of Contingency is a properly defined objective.
The explanation why so many worlds in SW Galaxy are 'desert' is because they were scourged by an earlier contingency vengeance campaign by failing Rakata Infinite Empire, around 25,600 BBY. Well , at least that is one explanation. THat is what happened to Tatooine . It was a lush ocean and jungle world, that was scourged by Rakata fleet, causing the water to boil away, and somehow Rakata excracted the water , drying the planet out.

snippet.textDisplay:
Palpatine is physically dead. The sith have the ability to possess inanimate objects. His acolytes had time to pull his body off the death star and after a stitch job and some mechanical modifications the zombie corpse of palpatine was ripe for possession.
For the sith this possession was necessary as it can be concluded the sith lineage lives through the rule of two. The master being the current vessel the sith occupy and the apprentice is the vessel the sith want to occupy next. When Vader redeemed himself, he broke the lineage and left palpatine no apprentice body for the spirits to move into after he died. It also explains why having an apprentice between Maul and Veder was necessary for Palpatine.

snippet.textDisplay: I think that Palpatine is the same Palpatine and not a clone. I think what happened in Return of the Jedi was that Palpatine did die. But before actually dying he may have used some Dark Side skill to re-enter his lifeless body. But he didn't fully come back to life. This is shown that his body is decaying when he shows his hands. I think he tried to clone his body, but he could not enter the clone body. So then he needed his own offspring. When he had his son, he probably sensed that he wasn't Force sensitive. But he did sense that his granddaughter was. And then concocted a plan to use his grand daughter's body for his soul to enter. Thus cheating death again.

snippet.textDisplay:
So, help me out. If Palpatine "made" Snoke, yet we see Snoke seconds away from having Rey killed by Kylo - which completely contradicts Palpatine's ultimate plan - are we supposed to assume, then, that Snoke was not a literal puppet, rather someone Palpatine influence in the shadows? This is what I don't get about the whole making Snoke a clone. To me, it only makes sense as I describe, because Snoke's personality and motivations and plans appear on their face completely at odds with what Palps says he's trying to do in ROS.


And really, this kind of brings up the problems of having a First Order and Final Order. Why even create Snoke and the First Order in the first place, which risks creating conflict with the Final Order? And we see a bit of that in the movie where some of the First Order generals are highly skeptical of the Final Order. The First Order seems as blindsided by Palpatine's return as the rest of the galaxy is.

What I think? TLJ wrote the series into a corner, JJ and crew had to get out of it with Snoke dead and not bringing him back, further, make people want to see this after being severely disappointed.

Very first trailer, brings Palps back...it was a cop out to get away from what TLJ did, and retcon as much as possible. If this was "the plan", then Palps would have been teased in the third act of TLJ. This was very rushed to explain everything, but could have taken some dead space in TLJ to fully embrace.
